  <h2>Montana Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Montana is a “microclimate state.” Elevation, exposure, and cold-air drainage can shift your effective season by weeks,
    even within the same town. Use your nearest station as the baseline, then adjust for what your yard actually does.
  </p>

  <h3>1) Elevation sets the outer boundary</h3>
  <p>
    In higher-elevation areas, spring warms later and fall cools faster. Even when mid-summer days are hot,
    cool nights can slow heat-driven crops (tomatoes, peppers, squash) and compress your margin.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’re above ~4,000–5,000 ft, plan for shorter-season varieties and assume less reliable late warm-season planting.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Cold-air drainage creates “frost pockets”</h3>
  <p>
    Cold air flows downhill and pools in low spots. Valley bottoms and depressions often frost earlier than nearby benches,
    slopes, and well-exposed sites. A difference of 10–30 feet in elevation can matter on clear, calm nights.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>If you’re in a low spot:</strong> treat median frost dates as optimistic.</li>
    <li><strong>If you’re on a bench/slope with airflow:</strong> you may run slightly warmer than the nearest station.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="small muted">
    Practical rule: add a 7–10 day safety buffer (or more) if you’ve seen repeated early frosts in your yard.
  </p>

  <h3>3) Big sun doesn’t guarantee a long finish</h3>
  <p>
    Montana’s long summer days can accelerate growth mid-season, but late-season cooling can arrive quickly.
    By early August in many locations, the strategy often shifts from “start new warm crops” to
    harvest + fall planting + season extension.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’re considering warm-season planting after mid-summer, assume you’ll need protection (row cover / low tunnel)
    and choose shorter-maturity varieties.
  </p>

</section>